---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="About · Schools of the Republic"
      description="Schools of the Republic — a public library of America's school trust lands, by the Advocates for School Trust Lands. Mission, team, substrate, and methodology."
    />
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-archive-paper text-ink" data-source-id="about-page">
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-prose p-4 sm:p-8">
      <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
        <h1>About this library</h1>

        <p>
          <em>Schools of the Republic</em> is a public library of America's school trust lands.
          Three rooms are live today — the Reading Room (the synthesizing argument and a
          per-state encyclopedia entry for every state), the Atlas (one map under four lenses),
          and the Counting House (the financial table with a confidence badge on every figure).
          Three more rooms — Records Room (curated primary sources), Court Room (case law and
          litigation timelines), and Breach &amp; Recovery (drift case studies) — open over the
          course of 2026. The library exists because the country gave itself a forever gift in
          1785 and then mostly forgot it; this is one attempt to make the inheritance legible
          again.
        </p>

        <h2>The team</h2>

        <p>
          The library is a project of the <strong>Advocates for School Trust Lands</strong>.
          Editorial responsibility currently rests with a small core team:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Dave Sullivan</strong> — CEO; co-author of <em>Schools of the Republic</em>
            and the <em>Sacred Compact</em> white paper. Strategic direction, substrate
            maintenance, and final review of public-facing work.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Margaret Bird</strong> — co-author and domain expert; longtime national
            authority on school-trust-lands law and policy. Substantive review of book chapters
            and trustee-facing memos.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Daniel Zene Crowe</strong> — OASTL General Counsel; lead on the live
            Coos County litigation (<em>24CV38372</em>) and its appellate posture.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Natalie Scott</strong> — case lead on the prior Coos County matter
            (<em>23CV39056</em>) and the Oregon Supreme Court petition (<em>S072734</em>);
            drafting, filing, and citation discipline.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Laura</strong> — legal research bridge across both cases.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The substrate</h2>

        <p>
          Every page on this site renders from a hand-curated source document — the
          <em>Schools of the Republic</em> v1.3 substrate — held in a private repository and
          never published verbatim. The Reading Room essays are derived from the synthesizing
          book and the <em>Sacred Compact</em> white paper. The Atlas and Counting House are
          built at compile time from per-state frontmatter. Primary sources cited across the
          library include federal admission acts, state constitutions, court opinions in the
          school-trust line, attorneys-general opinions, state land department reports and
          newsroom documents, and materials filed in the live Coos County litigation.
        </p>

        <h2>The methodology</h2>

        <p>
          The site is organized around a small set of editorial commitments. <em>Visible
          incompleteness</em>: where a state has not publicly disclosed a figure, the substrate
          says so with an "Awaiting State Disclosures" badge rather than guessing or omitting
          the row; where a state structurally has no federal trust, the cell shows an em-dash
          (an "authoritative no") rather than reading as a data gap. <em>Single source of
          truth</em>: every figure on the Atlas, the Counting House, and the per-state cards is
          derived at build time from the same per-state frontmatter, so the rooms cannot drift
          apart. <em>Six-room library architecture</em>: the surfaces are organized as rooms in
          a working library, not as marketing pages, and three of those rooms are explicitly
          marked "opening later" rather than dressed up as finished today. <em>Extensibility
          seams</em>: the source-id, room, and state metadata threaded through every page exist
          so that the future feedback form, programmatic API, and Records Room intake workflows
          can latch onto a stable substrate without retrofitting six rooms of templates.
        </p>

        <h2>How to contribute</h2>

        <p>
          Corrections, citation requests, and methodology questions are welcome. For now the
          intake mechanism is GitHub Issues at the
          <a
            href="https://github.com/dave-schooltrustlands/schooltrustlands-encyclopedia"
            rel="noopener"
            >project repository</a>; a public <code>/feedback/</code> form opens once the
          underlying intake workflow exists. If you have a public source for a figure
          currently flagged "Awaiting State Disclosures," please attach it on an issue — the
          Records Room (when it opens) will accept those contributions directly.
        </p>

        <h2>Toward a Public Ledger</h2>

        <p>
          What you see today is the encyclopedia floor. The library is being built toward a
          parcel-level, drillable, public ledger of the school-trust system — a structure that
          grows from this floor, state by state. The short public framing of that direction is
          on a separate page: <a href="/about/future-ledger/">Toward a Public Ledger →</a>.
          The full strategic essay is in the Reading Room as
          <a href="/reading/the-eighth-anchor/"><em>The Eighth Anchor</em></a>.
        </p>

        <h2>How to cite</h2>

        <p>
          Cite individual entries as: <em>Sullivan and Bird, Schools of the Republic v1.3,
          schooltrustlands.net/&#123;path&#125;/, retrieved YYYY-MM-DD.</em> A pre-filled
          citation appears in the footer of every page.
        </p>

        <h2>Technical notes</h2>

        <p>
          The site is operated by an interim entity, the Operating Advocates for School Trust
          Lands (OASTL), pending the formal adoption of a successor organization, Advocates for
          School Trust Lands (ASTL). OASTL exists to carry the public-facing scholarship and
          advocacy work forward without waiting on the corporate steps.
        </p>

        <p>
          Each per-state entry is generated by a Python migration script that extracts
          bibliographic frontmatter and a subset of quantitative fields (federal grant acres,
          governance form, permanent-fund corpus, latest distribution) from the v0.4 substrate
          and renders each state as an Astro content page. The migration is merge-preserving:
          hand-edited values on the website are never overwritten by re-running the script.
          The site is a static build deployed on Cloudflare Pages; there is no database and no
          server-side runtime.
        </p>

        <p>
          As of substrate v1.3, only one state (Oregon) has fully hand-verified financial
          figures plus per-state editorial copy in the dossier card. The other forty-nine carry
          partial data: most have a federal grant acreage and a governance description, but
          permanent-fund corpus and latest-distribution figures are populated only when the
          substrate value is unambiguous and pinned to a date. Where a year is given but no
          calendar day, the date field is left null rather than fabricated. Per-state editorial
          copy will hydrate over time as the editorial workstream catches up to the
          substrate.
        </p>

        <p>
          The visual design is interim. There is no logo, no signature typeface, and no brand
          color system yet; those decisions are deferred until they can be made deliberately
          rather than by default.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
